1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:18,800
 So you are welcome to ask questions to three of them.

2
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:20,560
 We have a mic over here.

3
00:00:20,560 --> 00:00:25,400
 You can come over here in the centre of the hall.

4
00:00:25,400 --> 00:00:31,840
 Before that, Mark, do you have any further comment to their response?

5
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:35,800
 Well, I appreciated what both of you shared.

6
00:00:35,800 --> 00:00:42,120
 First, it's absolutely true, this relevance is always, that's partly why I use the image

7
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:47,480
 of relevance from above and relevance from beneath, or from below, because the actual

8
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:53,320
 facts on the ground have to be made to be the stuff out of which the relevance from

9
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:57,160
 above is actually able to even be heard or understood.

10
00:00:57,160 --> 00:01:01,520
 But without the relevance from above, in the way I'm intending it, it's meant not to be

11
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:06,200
 an imposition, but a revelation, which has to actually be given to us and which is true

12
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:10,320
 regardless of what's happening below.

13
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:15,080
 But I appreciated very much the challenges, really, of how do you actually truly do this

14
00:01:15,080 --> 00:01:21,960
 in a way where there might be avoidance, denial, rejection, shame, fear, so many things that

15
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:26,240
 are part of what hampers our conversation, among other things.

16
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:28,180
 So certainly I appreciated that.

17
00:01:28,180 --> 00:01:33,800
 And I think I would just say about beauty, there's more to be said if people want to

18
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:39,600
 explore this, but I just think that we worship a god of beauty, a god who has fashioned a

19
00:01:39,600 --> 00:01:40,600
 world of beauty.

20
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:43,200
 You just have to live in Hong Kong to know that.

21
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:50,840
 I mean, this is a beautiful, remarkably beautiful place, and in such a concentrated form.

22
00:01:50,840 --> 00:01:55,800
 Both the beauty of all the human beings that are here, let me start with that, but also

23
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:59,240
 the physical creation space.

24
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:03,880
 So when I say the church needs to be beautiful, what I mean is that it needs to be a church

25
00:02:03,880 --> 00:02:11,600
 that lives its life out of the beauty of human relationships, out of the beauty of compassion,

26
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:18,480
 out of the beauty of forgiveness, out of the beauty of an acknowledgment of wrongdoing

27
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:23,640
 and the restoration of relationships, it's out of an unexpectedness of a willingness

28
00:02:23,640 --> 00:02:27,280
 to be self-giving, to lay down power.

29
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:30,640
 These are all beautiful things.

30
00:02:30,640 --> 00:02:36,680
 Whether people all receive them equally as beautiful, of course, beauty, as they say,

31
00:02:36,680 --> 00:02:38,800
 is in the eye of the beholder.

32
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:40,200
 That I think is taken for granted.

33
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:44,720
 I'm meaning it more from the sense of, is the church living in such a way that the beauty

34
00:02:44,720 --> 00:02:51,480
 of God's intention of a new creation is being shown whether or not people accept or reject

35
00:02:51,480 --> 00:02:58,760
 it in the same way that, for example, just this week, Apple Computer, as you may know,

36
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:03,200
 released a new iPad, and in the context of that, they made a video, which perhaps many

37
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:08,520
 of you have seen, which is this video of a press machine that's pressing down on all

38
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:15,640
 kinds of instruments of human creativity and crushing them, and then when it slowly lifts,

39
00:03:15,640 --> 00:03:18,840
 it has this iPad.

40
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:21,320
 I could not believe it.

41
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:25,680
 I felt like this was, Apple has made many serious mistakes in the way that they tell

42
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:28,780
 their story, but this was maybe the worst of all.

43
00:03:28,780 --> 00:03:35,760
 This was saying the beauty of all human activity that has manifested itself in crafts and arts

44
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:40,360
 and instrumentation and imagination.

45
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:45,080
 It all gets smashed, and all you need is an iPad.

46
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:49,160
 It was just like, that is repulsive.

47
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:56,920
 So what I don't mean by beauty is anything remotely like technical power, something like

48
00:03:56,920 --> 00:04:03,800
 imposition, something like an eradication of the smallest gestures.

49
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:08,840
 I've been recommending to some people this really amazing film that has come out recently

50
00:04:08,840 --> 00:04:16,640
 called Perfect Days, and it's a film about a Japanese man.

51
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:20,720
 I won't tell you, go into the details of the story, but it's the way that he lives the

52
00:04:20,720 --> 00:04:30,520
 beauty of his life in the most tiny, routine ways that are filled with human dignity.

53
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:32,560
 That's what I mean about a church in beauty.

54
00:04:32,560 --> 00:04:40,080
 In the most ordinary of ways, we treasure who God has made, we see one another, we feel

55
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:41,080
 with one another.

56
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:46,000
 Those are absolute beauty to me, and I think that church absolutely is doing that.

57
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,880
 But if it needs to be more of that, then so.

58
00:04:49,880 --> 00:04:52,480
 So anyway, those are just two quick comments.

59
00:04:52,480 --> 00:04:55,360
 The power or the beauty of service.

60
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:57,640
 The beauty of powerful love.

61
00:04:57,640 --> 00:04:58,640
 Right.

62
00:04:58,640 --> 00:04:59,640
 Wonderful.

63
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:00,640
 All right.

64
00:05:00,640 --> 00:05:01,640
 Okay.

65
00:05:01,640 --> 00:05:02,640
 Thank you.

66
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:07,880
 Anyone like to come over and ask any question or make any comment, please come over here,

67
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:08,880
 please.

68
00:05:08,880 --> 00:05:14,800
 Perhaps you would like to first mention your name and then to ask your question or make

69
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:17,320
 comment.

70
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:23,440
 In this occasion, I should actually better speak in English, but because I want to express

71
00:05:23,440 --> 00:05:27,320
 myself more fully, so excuse me, I have to speak in Cantonese.

72
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:31,840
 There are a few questions that I would like to ask.

73
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:37,680
 The topic that we are talking about today is relevance, but I think in Hong Kong, if

74
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:45,520
 we are talking about relevance, first we have to talk about the beginning and the end, identification.

75
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:57,840
 If we don't identify with our society, the pain and suffering, then we are talking about

76
00:05:57,840 --> 00:05:58,840
 relevance.

77
00:05:58,840 --> 00:06:16,400
 So, I think when I was listening, I was hoping that Dr. Levitin would talk more about a more

78
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:29,280
 down-to-earth insight, but he was talking about the feeling of going back to school

79
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:35,920
 and teaching, and then you have to digest it yourself to be able to explain it.

80
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:38,040
 So, I think, would it be…

81
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:44,880
 In fact, in Hong Kong, I was appreciating Dr. Leivitin, he was very brave to speak.

82
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:52,200
 In fact, what he said, if it were to go public, it would be a big problem.

83
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:58,960
 So, I think when we talk about relevance, the first thing is to start from our situation.

84
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:04,280
 In Hong Kong, as Dr. Leivitin just said, in the past 50 years, it was very easy for us

85
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:10,000
 to identify with the embodiment of Hong Kong society, because when we did some old-fashioned

86
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:15,480
 politics, it was very easy, you wouldn't offend anyone, but today, when we are talking about

87
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:19,040
 embodiment, you have to be political.

88
00:07:19,040 --> 00:07:23,480
 Why are so many people emigrating, especially the Hong Kong Church?

89
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:28,840
 In fact, I think the biggest problem is that a lot of pastors, a lot of leaders, they have

90
00:07:28,840 --> 00:07:29,840
 left.

91
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:30,840
 I know…

92
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:36,240
 Because my pastor's church used to be in Shatin, there was a church, a few years ago,

93
00:07:36,240 --> 00:07:42,680
 about 1,000 people, a church was about 1,000 people, it was about 4,000 people, about 1,000

94
00:07:42,680 --> 00:07:43,680
 people left.

95
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:47,920
 So, when we say we have to identify, we have to have relevance, if we don't start from

96
00:07:47,920 --> 00:07:54,640
 the identity, it is very difficult, but when we talk about identity, we will involve political

97
00:07:54,640 --> 00:07:55,640
 issues that are very sensitive.

98
00:07:55,640 --> 00:08:03,280
 So, this, or the pastors can give us some opinions, how do we identify, we won't cross

99
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:04,280
 the red line?

100
00:08:04,280 --> 00:08:11,880
 So, this is what we need to identify.

101
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:14,680
 Thank you very much for your questions.

102
00:08:14,680 --> 00:08:24,320
 First, let me just say that, as a guest to Hong Kong, and as a guest to CGST, I think

103
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:29,440
 one of the handicaps that I bring is that I can't be specific about Hong Kong.

104
00:08:29,440 --> 00:08:36,280
 I can, I would be presumptuous to do that, so I'm not obviously trying to do that.

105
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:41,760
 However, I do understand the point you're making about not wanting to leave things abstractly,

106
00:08:41,760 --> 00:08:46,800
 and if we had been able to, if I had been able to finish all that I had actually prepared,

107
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:53,120
 there was more that would have landed in the space that you were looking for, but, because,

108
00:08:53,120 --> 00:08:57,440
 so let me just, let me just offer a couple of things, so, and then the second question

109
00:08:57,440 --> 00:09:03,360
 was about, first one was about identity, and the second question was about how we, how

110
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:10,040
 we make this, how we have honest conversation about things that we avoid talking about.

111
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:14,560
 Is that, are those the two primary issues?

112
00:09:14,560 --> 00:09:24,560
 Okay, so, so I do think that in a Christian understanding of identity, it does, it does

113
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:31,280
 ground itself first in that I am a creature of God, that I'm a disciple of Jesus Christ,

114
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:40,320
 that I belong to a certain family, that I am associated socially in a certain circle,

115
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:46,360
 which could be a function of, you might at that stage move into Hong Kong identity, you

116
00:09:46,360 --> 00:09:50,440
 might move into Chinese identity, you might move into ethnic identity, but those are things

117
00:09:50,440 --> 00:09:56,400
 that are down the list, but you have to decide how those things are ordered, so I would,

118
00:09:56,400 --> 00:10:00,920
 I would never myself want to start only with the Hong Kong identity, for example, or my

119
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:03,880
 citizenship in the United States.

120
00:10:03,880 --> 00:10:08,240
 If I'm interested in talking about things that are specifically Christian, then I would

121
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:12,560
 want to do that, but, for example, just to be candid with what you're, I think, getting

122
00:10:12,560 --> 00:10:16,000
 at, right now in the United States, as you know, there's this huge divide within the

123
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:21,760
 church about whether you are a supporter of Donald Trump or whether you're a supporter

124
00:10:21,760 --> 00:10:27,000
 of Joe Biden, and then you're, and then around that, there's the questions of are you more

125
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:32,280
 conservative in your politics or more liberal in your politics, and many other things, but

126
00:10:32,280 --> 00:10:36,980
 those are the biggest kind of categories, so let's imagine I was having a conversation

127
00:10:36,980 --> 00:10:41,800
 with somebody who was a secular person, or, do you want it to be a person outside the

128
00:10:41,800 --> 00:10:44,880
 church or a person inside the church?

129
00:10:44,880 --> 00:10:45,880
 Inside the church.

130
00:10:45,880 --> 00:10:51,680
 And I've talked, I've certainly spoken at churches where there's a division, and all

131
00:10:51,680 --> 00:10:54,880
 the red people sit over here and all the blue people sit over there.

132
00:10:54,880 --> 00:10:59,280
 No, they don't do that, but they do really do that.

133
00:10:59,280 --> 00:11:03,520
 They do it by realizing who are the people I'm most comfortable with in this church?

134
00:11:03,520 --> 00:11:10,480
 I'll sit with the people that are going to make me the least uncomfortable, so that does

135
00:11:10,480 --> 00:11:15,440
 really happen, and, but let's imagine that I'm with one or two of those, or maybe I'm

136
00:11:15,440 --> 00:11:20,380
 with two, one from each side, and they want to talk about this division, and I would want

137
00:11:20,380 --> 00:11:25,440
 to take it on straight ahead, like, what is it that's really, why exactly, what are you

138
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:26,960
 each defining?

139
00:11:26,960 --> 00:11:28,880
 What are the questions that it raises?

140
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:31,480
 Why is there a collision?

141
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:34,320
 What could potentially solve the collision?

142
00:11:34,320 --> 00:11:37,760
 And if there isn't a solution to the collision, which I think, technically speaking, there

143
00:11:37,760 --> 00:11:43,640
 isn't a solution to the collision, what are the things that could be constructively done

144
00:11:43,640 --> 00:11:46,580
 in a time right now where there's this division, right?

145
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:52,200
 So I think, for example, of a friend of mine who is the leader of an organization throughout

146
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:58,560
 the United States that creates what it calls courageous conversations, where it brings

147
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:02,560
 people together around these very difficult points of conversation.

148
00:12:02,560 --> 00:12:04,720
 It's intended for Christian people.

149
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:11,360
 They come specifically because they disagree with each other, and they have sustained conversations,

150
00:12:11,360 --> 00:12:16,080
 sometimes over a few weeks, sometimes it goes on for as much as a year, where the same group

151
00:12:16,080 --> 00:12:22,440
 of people would come together around a sequence of topics, and every time they get together,

152
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:27,160
 there's a huge range of opinion that's different.

153
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:32,760
 What they're trying to practice is what they call Christian peacemaking.

154
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:37,800
 So they would say, first of all, it's an attempt to be peacemakers by just being in the room

155
00:12:37,800 --> 00:12:43,000
 with each other and having this extended conversation regularly over time, which gives us a chance

156
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:47,080
 not just to talk about the topic, but to know one another, right?

157
00:12:47,080 --> 00:12:54,240
 So you may know the name, he's a writer in the United States, a social commentator named

158
00:12:54,240 --> 00:12:55,520
 David Brooks.

159
00:12:55,520 --> 00:13:01,000
 David Brooks says, "The question to ask someone is not why do you believe that, but how did

160
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,920
 you come to believe that?"

161
00:13:03,920 --> 00:13:09,400
 The why question is sort of a defensive question, justify yourself that you have this particular

162
00:13:09,400 --> 00:13:10,400
 opinion.

163
00:13:10,400 --> 00:13:16,500
 A how question is a storytelling question, how did it happen that you came to have this

164
00:13:16,500 --> 00:13:17,500
 conviction?

165
00:13:17,500 --> 00:13:22,240
 It invites someone to tell the story of events, people, circumstances, experiences they've

166
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:23,880
 had, et cetera, right?

167
00:13:23,880 --> 00:13:29,600
 So that would be an example of saying, here's a very simple construct, it's overt about

168
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:32,780
 its purpose, we're coming together because we don't agree.

169
00:13:32,780 --> 00:13:39,040
 We are all Christians, but we're going to come together in a regular pattern of respectful

170
00:13:39,040 --> 00:13:44,960
 or sometimes it's called civil conversation, but courageous because they know that it's

171
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:46,760
 going to be a heated conversation.

172
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:51,080
 There will be emotions and passions expressed that are in collision.

173
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:55,720
 Now I think that's an expression to me, a very practical on the ground expression of

174
00:13:55,720 --> 00:13:57,080
 how people can come together.

175
00:13:57,080 --> 00:14:03,680
 The thing that I don't know, but I think I have an intuition about in Hong Kong, is that

176
00:14:03,680 --> 00:14:10,600
 that might be a lot more politically risky than I think it's socially or politically

177
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:12,880
 risky in the United States.

178
00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:17,080
 So that does complicate these things.

179
00:14:17,080 --> 00:14:20,720
 As Jesus said, power does.

180
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:25,760
 Power does complicate things.

181
00:14:25,760 --> 00:14:28,400
 So that would be an example.

182
00:14:28,400 --> 00:14:32,800
 Do you want another example or is that at least a helpful gesture?

183
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:33,800
 >> Okay.

184
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:34,800
 Okay.

185
00:14:34,800 --> 00:14:35,800
 Yeah.

186
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:36,800
 Okay.

187
00:14:36,800 --> 00:14:37,800
 Yeah.

188
00:14:37,800 --> 00:14:38,800
 That's good.

189
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:39,800
 Okay.

190
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:40,800
 Please.

191
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:41,800
 Okay.

192
00:14:41,800 --> 00:14:44,560
 >> I have one more comment about identity.

193
00:14:44,560 --> 00:14:49,400
 I think we all have to remember our identity is the forgiven sinners.

194
00:14:49,400 --> 00:14:55,000
 I think in this very divisive term, people make different decisions.

195
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:58,200
 For example, immigration, should I leave or not leave?

196
00:14:58,200 --> 00:15:02,400
 I choose to stay in Hong Kong, but I do not have a young kid.

197
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:04,920
 I do not have -- my girls are all grown up.

198
00:15:04,920 --> 00:15:10,880
 What would I have done if I have three -- if my three girls are in primary three or four?

199
00:15:10,880 --> 00:15:11,880
 I don't know.

200
00:15:11,880 --> 00:15:15,720
 I won't know what I would choose unless I'm really in that situation.

201
00:15:15,720 --> 00:15:21,480
 So I think one of the things we really have to learn is to be graceful to one another.

202
00:15:21,480 --> 00:15:28,960
 We ask God to show us how I should be, you know, a graceful person to witness for the

203
00:15:28,960 --> 00:15:31,840
 truth -- to the truth, but in a humble way.

204
00:15:31,840 --> 00:15:37,120
 But I also accept the way that, you know, the Lord may lead other people to walk different

205
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:38,120
 paths.

206
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:41,120
 I think this kind of acceptance is very important at this time.

207
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:42,120
 >> Amen.

208
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:44,440
 >> May I add a little bit?

209
00:15:44,440 --> 00:15:52,320
 I wrote down a quote from the American journalist, like, Henry Louis Mencken.

210
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:57,280
 He says, like, when people talk, they need religion.

211
00:15:57,280 --> 00:16:10,040
 In actual, they want police, because we want someone to be a judge to crush down the opposition.

212
00:16:10,040 --> 00:16:17,640
 I think as a church, as a people of God, when we try to have a conversation on divisive

213
00:16:17,640 --> 00:16:24,480
 topics, I think, at least to me, actually, most of the time, it's not about the topic

214
00:16:24,480 --> 00:16:27,400
 itself.

215
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:34,040
 Even though it is divisive, we try to deal with the stories behind, but especially the

216
00:16:34,040 --> 00:16:38,840
 sadness, the hurt, the disappointment.

217
00:16:38,840 --> 00:16:47,200
 I think if we have the courageous conversation, a lot of time, we can still disagree on many

218
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:53,920
 things, but we are together because we feel sadness, we feel hurt.

219
00:16:53,920 --> 00:16:56,520
 It's not because you do not agree with me, so I feel hurt.

220
00:16:56,520 --> 00:16:57,920
 No, not that.

221
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:02,920
 But because we think we are no longer together.

222
00:17:02,920 --> 00:17:06,960
 The separation really hurts the relationship.

223
00:17:06,960 --> 00:17:11,360
 I think that's the disappointment we have to deal with.

224
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:16,680
 I think that one of the main factors to the culture of indifference is because we will

225
00:17:16,680 --> 00:17:23,600
 disagree on everything, right, because why waste time on discussing?

226
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:29,080
 But to deal deep down, I think at least it helps to rebuild something.

227
00:17:29,080 --> 00:17:34,440
 Yeah, and I would only add to that that I think one of the most influential factors

228
00:17:34,440 --> 00:17:37,440
 emotionally is fear.

229
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:43,800
