457
00:35:38,160 --> 00:35:41,240
 This only happens once a year, so how does the regular gardening happen?"

458
00:35:41,240 --> 00:35:44,700
 They said, "Well, we don't really have anybody to do that, and the government doesn't pay

459
00:35:44,700 --> 00:35:45,700
 for it."

460
00:35:45,700 --> 00:35:52,680
 So they said, "Oh, well, then we'd like to come and clean up this area every month.

461
00:35:52,680 --> 00:35:56,680
 This is a considerable distance, this is probably 40 miles from where this church is actually

462
00:35:56,680 --> 00:36:00,160
 located," because they were in another part of the Bay Area.

463
00:36:00,160 --> 00:36:06,400
 So every month, they went as a group to clean up that area of the park.

464
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:09,720
 And as they did that, of course, they became friends with all the people that were coming

465
00:36:09,720 --> 00:36:14,160
 there to honor their friends or family members who had died with HIV/AIDS.

466
00:36:14,160 --> 00:36:21,400
 So much trust was built with this group, and they knew that this church was not pro-LGBTQIA,

467
00:36:21,400 --> 00:36:26,520
 but the church was not there to make a stand about their position on LGBT.

468
00:36:26,520 --> 00:36:34,480
 It was to actually just love people for whatever reasons and circumstances are in this place.

469
00:36:34,480 --> 00:36:39,880
 So amazingly, the people that are kind of the official people that oversee this part

470
00:36:39,880 --> 00:36:46,040
 of the park, who are all LGBT people, said, "We have this big annual gathering in the

471
00:36:46,040 --> 00:36:51,440
 park where we invite everyone around the whole United States, or the world, if they want

472
00:36:51,440 --> 00:36:58,040
 to come there, to come to a weekend where the AIDS quilt, which you may know about,

473
00:36:58,040 --> 00:37:07,040
 this gigantic quilt, is there, and then we have special events in this part of the park.

474
00:37:07,040 --> 00:37:13,480
 Would you be willing to organize and host that for us?"

475
00:37:13,480 --> 00:37:18,300
 So that no LGBTQIA people had to themselves do this.

476
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:19,680
 This would just be done for them.

477
00:37:19,680 --> 00:37:24,840
 So imagine the trust that had grown that they would say, "We're going to turn our event

478
00:37:24,840 --> 00:37:31,800
 over to you, who don't affirm our life, our lifestyle, our circumstances, but we've learned

479
00:37:31,800 --> 00:37:32,800
 to trust you.

480
00:37:32,800 --> 00:37:34,080
 You have loved us.

481
00:37:34,080 --> 00:37:36,180
 We have learned to love you.

482
00:37:36,180 --> 00:37:37,640
 We would like you to come."

483
00:37:37,640 --> 00:37:45,080
 So for five years, before it shifted to another group that needed to make these decisions,

484
00:37:45,080 --> 00:37:48,560
 for five years that church hosted that annual gathering.

485
00:37:48,560 --> 00:37:52,500
 Now when I think about the LGBT issue, I think about that.

486
00:37:52,500 --> 00:37:58,720
 I think about an AIDS hospice in San Francisco that used to listen together to sermons that

487
00:37:58,720 --> 00:38:02,200
 I was preaching that were carried on the radio.

488
00:38:02,200 --> 00:38:07,400
 And I just knew one person was there, but he invited me to come and meet with this whole

489
00:38:07,400 --> 00:38:13,080
 group of people, all of whom died of HIV/AIDS within the next year and a half from the first

490
00:38:13,080 --> 00:38:15,960
 time I visited them.

491
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:22,540
 In this group, all of them had come from Christian families whose families had rejected them.

492
00:38:22,540 --> 00:38:30,040
 So they were a family together, and they struggled in their dying with how to make peace with

493
00:38:30,040 --> 00:38:35,640
 their faith because the people that they knew best were the people that had most rejected

494
00:38:35,640 --> 00:38:36,840
 them.

495
00:38:36,840 --> 00:38:40,400
 Their Christian family parents, grandparents.

496
00:38:40,400 --> 00:38:48,120
 So I went and periodically met with them, and over the course of that year, almost every

497
00:38:48,120 --> 00:38:55,280
 time I went, more people had died until eventually every single person in that group had died.

498
00:38:55,280 --> 00:39:01,320
 And it was a story, again, of just trying to be present, trying to be compassionate.

499
00:39:01,320 --> 00:39:05,800
 I was never put in a position of having to explain or justify myself.

500
00:39:05,800 --> 00:39:07,920
 I take a traditional view.

501
00:39:07,920 --> 00:39:11,180
 So it was an example.

502
00:39:11,180 --> 00:39:12,920
 These are both examples to me.

503
00:39:12,920 --> 00:39:17,480
 I was led to do that, what I did, because of the example of this church.

504
00:39:17,480 --> 00:39:24,280
 I thought, well, if they can do that, surely I can just show up and be present, pray with

505
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:29,960
 them while they were dying, because they didn't know any other Christian person that would

506
00:39:29,960 --> 00:39:31,520
 do that.

507
00:39:31,520 --> 00:39:35,520
 So there are lots of ways, unexpected ways.

508
00:39:35,520 --> 00:39:36,860
 Are we praying for opportunity?

509
00:39:36,860 --> 00:39:43,760
 Are we praying for compassion so that it's not an object but really an act of love?

510
00:39:43,760 --> 00:39:45,520
 You're just trying to love them.

511
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:47,560
 That's all you're trying to do.

512
00:39:47,560 --> 00:39:52,520
 And yeah, so that was a very important experience for me.

513
00:39:52,520 --> 00:39:53,520
 >> Radical love.

514
00:39:53,520 --> 00:39:54,520
 >> Yeah.

515
00:39:54,520 --> 00:39:56,080
 >> Just a footnote.

516
00:39:56,080 --> 00:40:06,000
 CGST student body has invited the pastor of a pro-LGBTQ pastor actually to come and speak

517
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:08,240
 to the students once.

518
00:40:08,240 --> 00:40:14,200
 But unfortunately, that church hasn't invited me or any teachers to preach at that church.

519
00:40:14,200 --> 00:40:15,200
 [ Laughter ]

520
00:40:15,200 --> 00:40:16,200
 >> There's time.

521
00:40:16,200 --> 00:40:17,200
 >> So unfortunately.

522
00:40:17,200 --> 00:40:18,200
 >> There's still time.

523
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:19,200
 [ Laughter ]

524
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:20,200
 >> Okay.

525
00:40:20,200 --> 00:40:26,200
 Now, sorry about that, because time is running out, we can't allow any more questions.

526
00:40:26,200 --> 00:40:37,280
 So I must say, we thank you for Mark, Jackie, and Keane, your sharing is excellent and edifying

527
00:40:37,280 --> 00:40:38,440
 to us.

528
00:40:38,440 --> 00:40:42,720
 And also welcome all your questions.

529
00:40:42,720 --> 00:40:45,760
 And I think that the discussion is really, really good.

530
00:40:45,760 --> 00:40:56,160
 So thank you once again for coming, and may I ask Dr. Kamphai-Yu to say a closing prayer.

531
00:40:56,160 --> 00:40:57,160
 [ Laughter ]

532
00:40:57,160 --> 00:41:04,080
 >> Come on, come on, come on.

533
00:41:04,080 --> 00:41:05,080
 [ Laughter ]

534
00:41:05,080 --> 00:41:06,080
 >> Yeah.

535
00:41:06,080 --> 00:41:16,760
 >> Let us pray.

536
00:41:16,760 --> 00:41:24,260
 Lord we thank you for tonight's sharing.

537
00:41:24,260 --> 00:41:29,520
 We know that you are here with us.

538
00:41:29,520 --> 00:41:43,440
 We are challenged to be relevant, not merely to the world, but to be relevant to you, to

539
00:41:43,440 --> 00:41:50,240
 be relevant to the gospel.

540
00:41:50,240 --> 00:42:05,680
 Most too often we have forgotten, when we are doing theology here at this institution,

541
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:15,240
 we have to remind ourselves that theology is a science of critique, a critique whether

542
00:42:15,240 --> 00:42:20,960
 we are faithful to your word.

543
00:42:20,960 --> 00:42:26,600
 And being faithful to your word means faithful to the word incarnate.

544
00:42:26,600 --> 00:42:36,880
 And the first thing we have to ask ourselves is whether our theology is really faithful

545
00:42:36,880 --> 00:42:39,720
 to the word incarnate.

546
00:42:39,720 --> 00:42:53,620
 Does our theology reflect incarnation, the embodiment of your truth?

547
00:42:53,620 --> 00:43:06,000
 Before we bring the critique to the proclamation of the gospel, let us have reflection, deep

548
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:16,880
 reflection on the way we do theology, on the way we do theological reflection.

549
00:43:16,880 --> 00:43:27,360
 Before we set our eyes on the world, preparing to bring some critique to them, let us set

550
00:43:27,360 --> 00:43:39,520
 our eyes to ourselves, to our theological endeavor, and to the church.

551
00:43:39,520 --> 00:43:49,640
 Lord, help us to be humble, to be compassionate.

552
00:43:49,640 --> 00:44:05,520
 Help us to be true to the word incarnate, that we are ourselves the incarnate word.

553
00:44:05,520 --> 00:44:08,600
 In Jesus' name we pray.

554
00:44:08,600 --> 00:44:28,960
 Let's put our hands together and thank you, thank you, thank you, thank you.

